 |RiemannSum (f n) a b M - RiemannSum F a b M| < ε / 4`\n- `hNm : |RiemannSum (f m) a b M - RiemannSum F a b M| < ε / 4`\n\nBut our proof sketch only uses that these terms are non-negative, not their actual bounds. So in Lean, we can proceed as follows:\n\n1. Note that `ℓ m - ℓ n = [RiemannSum (f m) a b M - RiemannSum (f n) a b M] + [(RiemannSum (f n) a b M - ℓ n) - (RiemannSum (f m) a b M - ℓ m)]`\n   (but in Lean, we don't have this directly, because the Riemann sums are opaque).\n\n2. Instead, directly prove `|ℓ m - ℓ n| ≤ ...` by considering:\n   - `ℓ m - ℓ n = [ℓ m - RiemannSum (f m) a b M] + [RiemannSum (f m) a b M - RiemannSum (f n) a b M] + [RiemannSum (f n) a b M - ℓ n]` \n   - Then use the triangle inequality to get:\n     `|ℓ m - ℓ n| ≤ |ℓ m - RiemannSum (f m) a b M| + |RiemannSum (f m) a b M - RiemannSum (f n) a b M| + |RiemannSum (f n) a b M - ℓ n|` \n   - Finally, note that `|RiemannSum (f m) a b M - RiemannSum (f n) a b M| ≤ ...` (as in step 4).\n\nBut perhaps an easier approach is to realize that any expression of the form `|x - y|` can be bounded by `|x - z| + |z - w| + |w - y|` for any `z, w`. Here, we take `x = ℓ m`, `y = ℓ n`, and `z = RiemannSum (f m) a b M`, `w = RiemannSum (f n) a b M`. \n\nThen `|ℓ m - ℓ n| ≤ |ℓ m - RiemannSum (f m) a b M| + |RiemannSum (f m) a b M - RiemannSum (f n) a b M| + |RiemannSum (f n) a b M - ℓ n|`. \n\nThen, we further note that:\n`|RiemannSum (f m) a b M - RiemannSum (f n) a b M| ≤ |RiemannSum (f m) a b M - RiemannSum F a b M| + |RiemannSum F a b M - RiemannSum (f n) a b M|` (triangle inequality).\n\nThus, we get:\n`|ℓ m - ℓ n| ≤ |ℓ m - RiemannSum (f m) a b M| + |RiemannSum (f m) a b M - RiemannSum F a b M| + |RiemannSum (f n) a b M - RiemannSum F a b M| + |RiemannSum (f n) a b M - ℓ n|`.\n\nFinally, we note that `|ℓ m - RiemannSum (f m) a b M| = |RiemannSum (f m) a b M - ℓ m|`, and similarly for `n`.\n\nThis gives exactly the RHS in Lean, except that we have an extra term `|RiemannSum (f n) a b M - RiemannSum F a b M|` instead of `|RiemannSum (f n) a b M - ℓ n|`.\n\nWait no: Actually, the above steps give exactly the inequality we need! \n\nBecause by the triangle inequality:\n`|ℓ m - ℓ n| ≤ |ℓ m - RiemannSum (f m) a b M| + |RiemannSum (f m) a b M - RiemannSum (f n) a b M| + |RiemannSum (f n) a b M - ℓ n|`\n\nAnd then:\n`|RiemannSum (f m) a b M - RiemannSum (f n) a b M| ≤ |RiemannSum (f m) a b M - RiemannSum F a b M| + |RiemannSum (f n) a b M - RiemannSum F a b M|`\n\nThus:\n`|ℓ m - ℓ n| ≤ |ℓ m - RiemannSum (f m) a b M| + |RiemannSum (f m) a b M - RiemannSum F a b M| + |RiemannSum (f n) a b M - RiemannSum F a b M| + |RiemannSum (f n) a b M - ℓ n|`\n\nBut we can reorder the last three terms as:\n`≤ |RiemannSum (f n) a b M - ℓ n| + |RiemannSum (f n) a b M - RiemannSum F a b M| + |RiemannSum (f m) a b M - RiemannSum F a b M| + |RiemannSum (f m) a b M - ℓ m|`\n\nWhich matches exactly the RHS in Lean, because `|ℓ m - RiemannSum (f m) a b M| = |RiemannSum (f m) a b M - ℓ m|`.\n\nTherefore, in Lean, we can:\n1. Write `ℓ m - ℓ n = (ℓ m - RiemannSum (f m) a b M) + (RiemannSum (f m) a b M - RiemannSum (f n) a b M) + (RiemannSum (f n) a b M - ℓ n)`\n2. Apply the triangle inequality to these three terms.\n3. Further bound `RiemannSum (f m) a b M - RiemannSum (f n) a b M` using the triangle inequality with `RiemannSum F a b M` as a midpoint.\n\n#### Step 6: Formalizing the Lean Proof\n\nHere's how we do it:\n1. Introduce `x = ℓ m - RiemannSum (f m) a b M`\n   `y = RiemannSum (f m) a b M - RiemannSum (f n) a b M`",
